ts movement, these writers, lovers of literature, were also challenging the institution of modern literature itself. This anthology demonstrates the vitality of the “red decade” long buried in modern Japanese literary history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aJapanese prose literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aProletariat in literature. 0aShort stories, Japanesey20th centuryvTranslations into English. 0aWorking classzJapanvFiction. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  ajapan, japanese, revolution, proletariat, proletarian literature, asia, fiction, literary studies, 20th century, modernization, inequality, imperialism, expansion, injustice, anthology, factory work, discrimination, poverty, oppression, leftist politics, leftism, short stories, personal, political, labor, realism, reality, children, family, art, artwork, anti-imperialism, internationalism, socialism, socialist, repression.1 aBowen-Struyk, Heather, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDenji, Kuroshima, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField, Norma, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFusao, Hayashi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHiroshi, Kawaguchi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyok-chu, Chang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIneko, Sata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKayo, Nagano, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKazuko, Murayama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKei, Moriyama, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKojiro, Hosono, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKoreh